## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

While researching today's topic I came across details from the **2014 Community Health Systems breach** — which I covered briefly on Day 13 in the context of the Heartbleed vulnerability, but want to revisit through the enterprise architecture lens.

The CHS breach affected approximately 4.5 million patients. Post-incident analysis revealed that the attackers entered through an internet-facing system, moved laterally through the network, and ultimately accessed patient data in systems that were not the original target. The lateral movement was possible because network segmentation between systems was insufficient — the enterprise architecture had not enforced boundaries between systems that should have been isolated from each other.

This is the architectural failure mode that today's work is designed to prevent. When OpenMRS is properly placed in a VPC with appropriate subnet architecture, security groups that restrict traffic between components, and monitoring that can detect lateral movement across the environment, the blast radius of any initial compromise is limited. An attacker who gains access to one system cannot automatically pivot to OpenMRS — they have to cross the architectural boundaries, which should generate detection events.

Enterprise architecture alignment is not just about making systems work together efficiently. It is about ensuring that the security boundaries are designed into the architecture, not bolted on afterward.

