## What I Am Still Thinking About

One practical question that this work raised: how should the enterprise architecture documentation for OpenMRS be maintained as the environment evolves?

The architecture diagram I documented today accurately represents the current deployment. But as new integrations are added, as the identity management approach evolves, as monitoring capabilities mature, the architecture changes. If the documentation does not keep pace with the system, it loses its value as an accurate representation of the security boundary and the control environment.

The answer is probably change management — requiring that architecture-affecting changes go through a review process that includes updating the SSP and architecture documentation before the change is implemented. That connects to the change management question I raised at the end of Day 34 on boundary definition. I want to develop a lightweight change management process for the MyClinic context that is practical for a small organization without becoming a bureaucratic obstacle to necessary operational changes.

